{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019tXMs419e6GNPqTAxLRYmn","type":"tool_result","content":"316\t    let co = match up {\n317\t        LuaValue::Thread(t) => t,\n318\t        _ => {\n319\t            return Err(LuaError::runtime(format_args!(\n320\t                \"coroutine.wrap: upvalue is not a thread\"\n321\t            )))\n322\t        }\n323\t    };\n324\t    let narg = state.get_top();\n325\t    let r = aux_resume(state, co, narg);\n326\t    if r < 0 {\n327\t        let top = state.get_top();\n328\t        let err_val = state.value_at(top);\n329\t        Err(LuaError::from_value(err_val))\n330\t    } else {\n331\t        Ok(r as usize)\n332\t    }\n333\t}\n334\t\n335\t/// Close all open upvalues of `val` (and transitively of any Lua closures\n336\t/// it refers to) by copying their current values from the parent thread's\n337\t/// stack into the `UpVal` struct.\n338\t///\n339\t/// When a closure is transferred to a new coroutine, its open upvalues\n340\t/// point into the parent thread's stack by `StackIdx`. The coroutine has\n341\t/// its own separate `stack` Vec, so reading an open upvalue from inside\n342\t/// the coroutine would access the wrong slot. Closing upvalues before\n343\t/// transfer converts `Open { idx }` → `Closed(current_value)`, making\n344\t/// the value self-contained and accessible across thread boundaries.\n345\t///"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b67c0d92-bbd3-456a-9ef8-983f2f784534","uuid":"7b0d6d7d-76cd-4f2a-8cea-8735a165218f","timestamp":"2026-05-19T04:17:25.924Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/ianmclaughlin/PycharmProjects/rustExperiments/lua-rs-port/crates/lua-stdlib/src/coro_lib.rs","content":"    let co = match up {\n        LuaValue::Thread(t) => t,\n        _ => {\n            return Err(LuaError::runtime(format_args!(\n                \"coroutine.wrap: upvalue is not a thread\"\n            )))\n        }\n    };\n    let narg = state.get_top();